Steps to Reproduce:


1. Create a new project and change the first lines of `HelloWorld::init` to the following:

```cpp
    //////////////////////////////
    // 1. super init first
    if ( !Scene::initWithPhysics() )
    {
        return false;
    }

	this->getPhysicsWorld()->setDebugDrawMask(false);
```

2. Run the application and it will crash.

- cocos2d-x version: 3.15.0
- devices test on: Samsung Galaxy Tablet Android 4.4.2
- developing environments
   - NDK version: Android Studio r14B

Steps to Reproduce:

If you make multiple edits to the draw node and clear and then draw, sometimes the draw node remains empty. With the following example, the draw node will flash continually.

On iOS, the drawing will stay constant; while on Android, the drawing flashes continually. As a work around, I am creating a draw node every time.

`void MyNode::visit(Renderer* renderer, const Mat4& parentTransform, uint32_t parentFlags)
{

    _drawNode->clear();
    _drawNode->drawDot(Point(10.0f, 10.0f), 10.0f, Color4F::BLACK);

    // Super
    Node::visit(renderer, parentTransform, parentFlags);
}`

When i call `setNodePosition`, cocos throws me errors and all my nodes are like deleted

- cocos2d-x version: v.3.5
- devices test on: simulator (720 x 1280)
Steps to Reproduce:

1. Creating an `UI layout node`, and linking it with this `script:`
<pre>
const {ccclass, property} = cc._decorator;

@ccclass
export default class MouseHandler extends cc.Component
{

    constructor ()
    {
        this.onMouseMove = onMouseMove
        this.setNodePostion = setNodePostion
    }

    onLoad()
    {
        this.setNodePostion() // When this method is called -> bug
        this.node.on('mousemove', this.onMouseMove)        
    }
}


function setNodePostion () : void
{
    size : cc.Size = cc.director.getVisibleSize()
}

function onMouseMove ( event ) : void
{
    console.log( event.getLocationX() )
}
</pre>
2. Try to compile
3. Enjoy ! All nodes become unreachable!

The bug can be corrected with setNodePostion declared into the class but the "error handling" still bad ! cocos should say "that's not the good way !"
